    <h1 class="article-title">The Glowing Chemistry: How Glow Sticks Create Light</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Discover the fascinating world of chemiluminescence and learn how glow sticks produce brilliant light through chemical reactions without any heat</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">Phenyl oxalate ester + H₂O₂ + Fluorescent dye</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">Light + CO₂ + Phenol</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">When you crack a glow stick and watch it burst into colorful light, you're witnessing one of chemistry's most mesmerizing phenomena: chemiluminescence. Unlike the light from your lamp or the sun, this glow doesn't come from heat – it's the direct result of a chemical reaction that converts chemical energy into light energy with remarkable efficiency.</p>
  <p class="body-text">Inside every glow stick are two separate chambers containing different chemicals. The main chamber holds a phenyl oxalate ester (like CPPO - bis(2,4,6-trichlorophenyl)oxalate) dissolved in a solvent, along with a fluorescent dye that determines the color. The smaller inner tube contains hydrogen peroxide. When you bend the stick, the inner tube breaks, mixing these chemicals and starting the light-producing reaction.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">What Makes Chemiluminescence Special?</div>
    <div class="callout-text">Chemiluminescence is often called "cold light" because it produces light without significant heat. Regular incandescent bulbs waste about 95% of their energy as heat, but chemiluminescent reactions can achieve up to 90% efficiency in converting chemical energy directly to light!</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The magic happens when the phenyl oxalate ester reacts with hydrogen peroxide, creating an unstable intermediate compound. This intermediate transfers its excess energy to the fluorescent dye molecules, exciting their electrons to higher energy levels. As these excited electrons fall back to their ground state, they release the excess energy as photons – the light you see glowing from the stick. Different dyes produce different colors: 9,10-diphenylanthracene creates blue light, while rhodamine B produces red light.</p>

